More to point @revshark From a traders standpoint, if one shorted becasue of lousy jobs outlook and the #s came in far worse than expected, what does a trader do now? Isnt it not the news but the manner in which the markets respond a trading determinant? Teach me.

Buffett always averages in - it has nothing to do with the size of his portfolio. Remember a good portion of the existing portfolio has been in place for decades and is immovable. So he is moving around far more less than $250 billion. He is not a market timer

(he has made this abundantly clear) and he is not challenged by size. I just don't agree with your statement that he is mandated to be incremental. Take out largest five positions and his average portfolio position is well under $10 billion. He has a choice.
If you are a trader that shorted because the jobs data would be horrible - and that data has been reported and stocks dont go down... what do you do now?
